      <hedline>
        <hl1>Muscle Power</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Richard A Lowenstein letter on Aug 3 article on human-generated power says article missed one of early human-power-to-stored-energy devices: the self-winding watch (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The article on human-generated power made a useful distinction between the direct transfer of action to energy (as in pedal-powered bike lights) and stored-energy applications. But it missed one of the early (and still used) human-power-to-stored-energy devices: the self-winding watch. Eight hours of wearing one generated enough power to run the watch 24 hours a day.</p>
        <p>RICHARD A. LOWENSTEIN  Westport, Conn.</p>
      </block>
